04663nam a22005655i 9780773599161DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20162016xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735991617 a10.1515/97807735991612doi  a(DE-B1597)654753  a(OCoLC)1245678509  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aBX1422.Q8bA33 2016 7aREL0330002bisacsh04a971.4/712231 aAbbott, Frank A., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aBody or the Soul? :bReligion and Culture in a Quebec Parish, 1736-1901 /cFrank A. Abbott. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2016] 4c©2016  a1 online resource :b15 photos, 7 maps, 10 diagrams, 7 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aMcGill-Queen's Studies in the History of Religion ;v200tFront Matter -- tContents -- tFigures and Tables -- tAbbreviations -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tHabitants and Religion in Nineteenth-Century Québec -- tDevelopment and Transformation: St-Joseph-de-Beauce, 1736–1901 -- tRender unto God: Buildings and Belief -- tMinistering to a Rural Parish: The Curés of St-Joseph, 1761–1901 -- t“Holy Water and Candles”: Catholicism in St-Joseph -- tBeliefs, Superstitions, and Popular Spirituality -- tHoly Water versus Fire Water: Habitant Sociability and the Curés -- tSociability and Sexuality: “On danse pour le plaisir de danser” -- tConclusion -- tAppendix -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the two centuries before the Quiet Revolution, the people of Quebec exercised a higher degree of independence from the Catholic Church than is often presumed. Investigating rural Quebec from the mid-eighteenth century to the turn of the twentieth, Frank Abbott argues convincingly that the obligations and priorities of the Church did not unswervingly rule the lives of its parishioners. The Body or the Soul? is a history of religious and cultural life in the parish of St-Joseph-de-Beauce. Drawing from their pastors' detailed annual reports to the archbishops of Quebec, St-Joseph’s parish registers, contemporary accounts, government censuses, and the largely unexplored oral testimony on rural life and culture found in the Archives de folklore et ethnologie at Université Laval, Abbott assesses the nature and degree of influence and control that the church exerted over the everyday lives of a rural Quebec community. He examines the telling details found in church building projects, the relationships between clergy and parishioners, attendance at Sunday mass and catechism classes, reception of communion, the persistence of what the Church termed “superstition,” traditional customs of sociability, and the degree of control that the Church exerted over the community’s social and sexual behaviour. Rich with primary sources, The Body or the Soul? reveals the tensions between Catholicism’s place in people’s lives and the independent spirit of a vigorous popular culture.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aChurch and statezQuébec (Province)xHistory. 0aChurch and statezQuébec (Province)xHistory. 0aReligion and sociologyzQuébec (Province)zSaint-Joseph-de-Beauce. 0aReligion and sociologyzQuébec (Province)zSaint-Joseph-de-Beauce. 7aRELIGION / History.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311127380808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2016z978311127630440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077359916140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773599161423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773599161/original  a978-3-11-127380-8  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016